        "title": "One heart, one soul, no need — the Spirit's economic shape",
        "range": "4:32-37",
        "excerpt": "And the congregation of those who believed were of one heart and soul; and not one of them claimed that anything belonging to him was his own, but all things were common property to them.",
        "body": "Verses 32-37 are not an epilogue to the trial; they are its theological consequence. Luke's logic is consistent throughout Acts: bold proclamation (vv. 1-22) processed through corporate prayer (vv. 23-31) produces visible social transformation (vv. 32-37). The same Spirit who fills mouths in public reshapes pockets in private. The text says *the congregation of those who believed were of one heart and soul* — *kardia kai psychē mia*. Affective and volitional unity; not uniformity of opinion but unity of orientation.\n\nThe practical consequence is stated negatively first: *not one of them claimed that anything belonging to him was his own*. The verb is *elegen idion einai* — to *call one's own*. The possessive claim, not ownership itself, is renounced. Luke is not describing the abolition of private property (5:4 makes clear Ananias still owned his land and the proceeds afterward) but the renouncing of the *possessive instinct* that says *this is mine and not available to my brother*. Then the positive: *all things were common* (*hapanta koina*). The Greek philosophical ideal — *koina ta philōn*, *friends share all things* (Plato, *Republic* 424a; Aristotle, *NE* 1168b8) — is realized not by philosophy but by the Spirit.\n\nVerse 33 places resurrection witness at the heart of this community: *And with great power the apostles were giving testimony to the resurrection of the Lord Jesus, and abundant grace was upon them all.* The resurrection that incited the Sadducees (4:2) is the same resurrection the apostles continue to proclaim *with great power* — Luke uses *megalē dynamis*, matching the *dynamis* the Sanhedrin had asked about in 4:7. The community is generous because the apostles preach resurrection, and resurrection has reorganized their relationship to possessions. If Christ is risen and we will be raised, what we own becomes provisional in a way that frees us to share.\n\nThe outcome is the literal fulfillment of Deuteronomy 15:4 — *there will be no poor among you*. Luke says, *there was not a needy person among them* (4:34). The mechanism is voluntary: *all who were owners of land or houses would sell them and bring the proceeds of the sales and lay them at the apostles' feet* (4:34-35). The imperfect tense (*epōloun*, *epheron*) marks ongoing pattern — not a one-time liquidation but a continual practice. Distribution was need-based — *as any had need* — and apostolically administered. This is not socialism by mandate; it is *koinōnia* by Spirit. Coercion ruins it; that is precisely the lesson of Ananias and Sapphira in chapter 5.\n\nLuke ends the chapter with a named exemplar: *Joseph, a Levite of Cyprian birth, who was also called Barnabas by the apostles (which translated means Son of Encouragement), and who owned a tract of land, sold it and brought the money and laid it at the apostles' feet* (4:36-37). The name change matters — *Bar-nabas* (or possibly *bar-nebû'â*, son of prophecy, popularly etymologized as son of encouragement). Barnabas will become Paul's first sponsor (Acts 9:27), missionary partner (Acts 13:2), and the man who reaches for the failed John Mark when Paul will not (Acts 15:37-39). Luke plants his seed here, in this concrete act, on this page — and uses him later as the contrast to Ananias and Sapphira (5:1-11). The Spirit's normal product is named Barnabas; the counterfeit is named Ananias.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Homothumadon* (v. 24, contextually echoing v. 32) and *kardia kai psychē mia* (one heart and soul, v. 32) capture the affective-volitional unity. *Hapanta koina* (all things in common, v. 32) deliberately echoes Greek philosophical ideals only to show them realized by the Spirit, not by ideology. *Paraklēsis* (encouragement, v. 36) — the same word for the Holy Spirit's role as *Paraklētos* in John's Gospel; Barnabas embodies in human form what the Spirit does in the church."
